🧠 THE M&R AUDIT SYSTEM: WHAT YOU NEED TO KNOW
The Diagnostic Framework
The M&R Audit is built on a hierarchical framework:
5 Dimensions → Core pillars of business growth

Financial Health
Client Portfolio
Operations
Team Structure
Strategic Stewardship

25 Capability Areas (5 per dimension) → Buildable/fixable systems within each dimension

Examples: "Role Clarity & Delegation" (Team), "Cash Flow Forecasting" (Financial), "Client Qualification" (Client Portfolio)

125 Checkpoints (5 per capability) → Granular proof points assessed in the audit

Each checkpoint has a stage-calibrated urgency score (1-25)
User responses: Yes (2 points) / Somewhat (1 point) / No (0 points)
Checkpoints are ranked per dimension (1-25), not globally

The Two Core Metrics
Maturity Score:
Measures breadth of capability development. How fully are systems, processes, and operating rhythms developed relative to best practice for the user's stage?
Readiness Score:
Measures quality of maturity composition. Which checkpoints have been addressed? A founder can score high in maturity by nailing low-urgency items, but still lack the high-criticality foundations needed to scale. Maturity ≠ Readiness.
Stage Fit:
Each checkpoint is compared against typical expectations for the user's AE Ladder stage:

Below Stage — Underdeveloped for current stage (creates drag)
At Stage — Performing as expected (stable)
Ahead of Stage — Exceeds expectations (strength)


